data.content:
Here's what happened and how to fix it:

**Root cause:** C# 14 introduces new built-in span conversions. When you write `array.Contains(num)` on an `int[]`, the compiler now binds to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. The `MemoryExtensions` method **cannot be represented in an expression tree**, so it throws at runtime when the expression is compiled/interpreted.

**Fix — cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>`** to force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option A: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option B: explicit cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option C: call Enumerable.Contains directly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three force the compiler to pick the expression-tree-compatible `Enumerable.Contains` overload.
